## 2. Solution Overview

### Core Platform: RipEm

A unified app that functions as a "project brain" for any vehicle, storing and organizing:

#### Information Architecture

**Project Details**
- Vehicle make, model, year, VIN
- Purchase date, current status (active, archived, sold)
- Location/storage info
- Overall project goals and scope

**Parts Inventory**
- All parts (installed, in-progress, needed)
- Part name, part number, supplier/source
- Cost, purchase date, warranty info
- Installation date and notes
- Current location (installed, on shelf, in storage)

**Work History & Maintenance**
- Log entries (voice-transcribed or typed)
- Date, time spent, description of work
- Tools used, parts involved
- Before/after photos and videos
- Costs incurred

**Timeline & Scheduling**
- Maintenance schedule (oil changes, inspections, etc.)
- Upcoming tasks and deadlines
- Work history (when things were done, how often)

**Resources & Tools**
- Tools commonly used on this project
- Preferred suppliers and vendors
- Reference documents, manuals, links

### Three Core Features

#### Feature 1: Easy Voice-to-Log Entry System

Users simply pull out their phone and record a voice message about what they did:
- "Just replaced the spark plugs. Used Denso plugs from AutoZone, cost $45. Took about 30 minutes."
- AI transcribes and extracts: part name, supplier, cost, time spent
- Optional: Attach photos/videos
- AI automatically categorizes and logs into the project brain

**Why it works**: No friction. Users can document during or right after work, not days later when they've forgotten details.

#### Feature 2: Intelligent AI Assistant

The app includes an AI chat interface that understands the context of each user's specific project:
- **Question answering**: "What maintenance have I done on this vehicle?" → pulls from project history
- **Parts research**: "What's the best replacement for the OEM alternator?" → considers the car's specs, researches options, uses community data
- **Planning**: "What should I do next?" → suggests based on project phase, common best practices, community feedback
- **Cost analysis**: "How much did I spend on suspension work?" → aggregates and summarizes
- **Advice & best practices**: Uses trained data from multiple sources (forums, community builds, official docs)

**Privacy note**: Project data is private by default. Only shared data (build logs, completed projects) feed into the community knowledge base.

#### Feature 3: Build Blog Publishing & Community Discovery

Users can publish their work to a community feed:

**Publishing**
- Automatic option: AI compiles all work done in a week/month, writes a blog post with photos
- Manual option: User writes a custom post about a specific project phase
- Share to social (Instagram, Twitter, TikTok, or just keep on platform)

**Community Discovery**
- Feed shows build updates from users and their projects
- Users can subscribe to others' garages to follow along
- Upvote/downvote posts (like/dislike)
- Comments and discussion
- Video format option: AI auto-edits photos into a short video with voiceover or user narration

**Knowledge Loop**
- Community build data feeds back into the platform's AI training
- When users mark something as "successful" or "didn't work," that becomes data
- Over time, the platform learns the best approaches for specific car models and project types

